Feature: the bc-reviewer role template directs the sign-off work_done emit through the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper, not the bare "shop-msg respond work_done" primitive, so the wrapper's scenario_hashes-match precondition is reached on every sign-off

  Driver: lead-mab1 (re-scoped; architect layer disposition confirmed). Root cause on
  the installed artifact surface (shop-templates show bc-reviewer): the bc-reviewer
  template's "Sign-off -> work_done complete" outcome instructs the CONCRETE emit command
  as the BARE "shop-msg respond work_done --bc ... --scenario-hash <h> ...", while the
  preceding prose claims "the bc-emit work-done wrapper enforces these preconditions ...
  if your emit is refused, fix and retry". Because the instructed command is the bare
  messaging primitive, the wrapper is never invoked, the "refused, fix and retry" prose
  is dead, and the wrapper's orphan/stale/missing scenario-hash refusal is never reached.
  In the lead-jonx incident the reviewer followed the template literally and a typo'd
  orphan hash ('cc52003444ee7', not the pinned 'cc52003444ea63f7' for scenario 161)
  persisted to the lead inbox.

  This scenario pins the CORRECTED guidance: the sign-off "work_done complete" outcome
  must direct the emit through the "bc-emit work-done" WRAPPER (the path that runs the
  mechanically-checkable preconditions per ADR-036 D), and must scope the bare
  "shop-msg respond work_done --force" to forced recovery only.

  Coexistence (additive; none retired):
  - Scenario 179 @ea9c1bbd9be87d72 pins that the bc-emit work-done WRAPPER recomputes
    block-only scenario hashes and refuses on stale/missing/orphan. THIS scenario pins
    that the reviewer is actually routed through that wrapper, so 179's refusal is reached
    on the sign-off path. The two compose; 179 is unchanged.
  - Scenario 181 @f81ee56bc163934b pins that bare "shop-msg respond work_done --force"
    bypasses the wrapper as the forced-recovery escape valve. THIS scenario pins that the
    template names --force ONLY as that escape valve, not as the routine sign-off emit.
    The two compose; 181 is unchanged.
  - Scenario 189 @942895d284cf0ec7 gates that the templates' respond subsections name
    "shop-msg respond" per numbered step; its bc-reviewer row targets "## Outcomes". The
    Outcomes section is bullet-form (not numbered steps), and the clarify and
    work_done(blocked) outcomes still name "shop-msg respond"; "bc-emit work-done" is the
    wrapper over "shop-msg respond work_done". Architect to confirm the 189 interaction at
    assignment; neither scenario retires the other.

  Grounded against the installed artifact surface (ADR-018) via "shop-templates show
  bc-reviewer"; this scenario currently fails against the rendered template (which
  instructs the bare command) and is the pin for the request_bugfix fix.

  @scenario_hash:35d3af0c79b55fbf
  Scenario: the rendered bc-reviewer template directs the sign-off work_done emit through the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper and names bare "shop-msg respond work_done --force" only as the forced-recovery escape valve
    When I read the bc-reviewer template via "shop-templates show bc-reviewer"
    Then the sign-off "work_done complete" outcome names "bc-emit work-done" as the concrete command the reviewer runs to emit the sign-off
    And that sign-off outcome does NOT instruct a bare "shop-msg respond work_done" invocation as the command the reviewer runs to emit the sign-off
    And the bare "shop-msg respond work_done --force" path is named only as the forced-recovery escape valve, never as the routine sign-off emit
